# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alpheus-spring-packard
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He was born on December 23, 1798, in Chelmsford, Massachusetts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He graduated from Bowdoin College in 1816.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Packard was the son-in-law of Bowdoin College's second president, the Reverend Jesse Appleton, through his first marriage to Frances Appleton (1804–1839).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] McLellan after his wife's death and produced a fifth son, Robert L.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Packard, who graduated from Bowdoin in 1868.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Packard was a key figure in the Maine Historical Society from its founding in 1822 until his death in 1884.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He was also a prominent member of the Peucinian Society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Packard had a long-standing relationship with Bowdoin College.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He remained there for the remainder of his life, first as a tutor (1819–1824), and then as a professor of ancient language and classical literature (1824–1865).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] During the last two years of his life, he was acting president of the college.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] The Bowdoin College George Mitchell Special Collections department lists thirteen publications.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Among them, he edited and was joint author (with Nehemiah Cleaveland) of *The History of Bowdoin College, with Biographical Sketches of its Graduates* (1882); he also edited *Works of the Rev.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] Jesse Appleton, with a memoir* (1836–1837); and *Xenophon's Memorabilia of Socrates, with English Notes* (1839; third edition, 1843).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] To commemorate Packard's 65 years of service to Bowdoin College, the Alpheus Spring Packard Gateway was built on the pathway of College Avenue between Coles Tower and the main quad.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He is interred at Pine Grove Cemetery in Brunswick.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] He died on July 13, 1884, in Squirrel Island, Maine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] The Bowdoin College Russwurm African American Center located at 6 College St. in Brunswick, Maine was originally built in 1827 for Packard, who in 1836 sold half to William Smyth, professor of mathematics.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] For the next 35 years, the house was known as the Packard–Smyth House.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard-sr] The house has also been known as the Mitchell–Little house (after subsequent owners).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Packard was one of four sons of Alpheus Spring Packard Sr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] (1798–1884) and the brother of William Alfred Packard.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He was born in Brunswick, Maine, and went to the Bowdoin College where his father was a professor of Greek and Latin.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] His mother, Frances Elizabeth, who died shortly after his birth was the daughter of Rev.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Appleton who had served as president of Bowdoin College, and Alpha as he was known was raised by an aunt He was encouraged by Paul A.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Chadbourne of Williams College to take up zoology.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] As a member of the Lyceum of Natural History he joined an expedition to Labrador and Greenland.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] In 1861 he received his bachelors degree.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He went to Cambridge and studied under Louis Agassiz.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] His first publication in 1863 was on types in insects.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He also studied for his medical exams and received a doctor's degree in 1864.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He made another trip to Labrador along with the artist William Bradford and took a special interest in geology. was Professor of Zoology and Geology at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, from 1878 until his death.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He was a vocal proponent of Neo-Lamarckism during the eclipse of Darwinism.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] After college, he joined the Maine state as an entomologist.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] From 1862 to 1865 he was enlisted into the First Regiment of Maine Volunteers as an assistant surgeon.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] During the marches he collected insects.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] His chief work was the classification and anatomy of arthropods, and contributions to economic entomology, zoogeography, and the phylogeny and metamorphoses of insects.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] At Boston he became a librarian and custodian for the Boston Society of Natural History working also on his Labrador collections.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] In 1866 he went to the Peabody Academy of Science along with Putnam, Morse and Hyatt.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He left in 1878 to accept a position of professor of Zoology and Geology at Brown University.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Packard was appointed to the United States Entomological Commission in 1877 where he served with Charles Valentine Riley and Cyrus Thomas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He wrote school textbooks, such as *Zoölogy for High Schools and Colleges* (eleventh edition, 1904).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] His *Monograph of the Bombycine Moths of North America* was published in three parts (1895, 1905, 1915, edited by T.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society in 1878.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Packard married Elizabeth Darby Walcott, daughter of Samuel B.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Walcott in October 1867 in Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] They would have four children: Martha Walcott, Alpheus Appleton, Elizabeth Darby, and Frances Elizabeth.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] Elizabeth Darby would die at the age of eight.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/alpheus-spring-packard] He died on February 14, 1905, in Providence, Rhode Island, with his wife and children outliving him.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Haemolymph is the analogue of blood for most arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] An arthropod has an open circulatory system, with a body cavity called a haemocoel through which haemolymph circulates to the interior organs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Like their exteriors, the internal organs of arthropods are generally built of repeated segments.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] They have ladder-like nervous systems, with paired ventral nerve cords running through all segments and forming paired ganglia in each segment.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Their heads are formed by fusion of varying numbers of segments, and their brains are formed by fusion of the ganglia of these segments and encircle the esophagus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The respiratory and excretory systems of arthropods vary, depending as much on their environment as on the subphylum to which they belong.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods use combinations of compound eyes and pigment-pit ocelli for vision.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In most species, the ocelli can only detect the direction from which light is coming, and the compound eyes are the main source of information; however, in spiders, the main eyes are ocelli that can form images and, in a few cases, can swivel to track prey.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have a wide range of chemical and mechanical sensors, mostly based on modifications of the many bristles known as setae that project through their cuticles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Similarly, their reproduction and development are varied; all terrestrial species use internal fertilization, but this is sometimes by indirect transfer of the sperm via an appendage or the ground, rather than by direct injection.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Aquatic species use either internal or external fertilization.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Almost all arthropods lay eggs, with many species giving birth to live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Still, a few are genuinely viviparous, such as aphids.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropod hatchlings vary from miniature adults to grubs and caterpillars that lack jointed limbs and eventually undergo a total metamorphosis to produce the adult form.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The level of maternal care for hatchlings varies from nonexistent to the prolonged care provided by social insects.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The evolutionary ancestry of arthropods dates back to the Cambrian period.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The group is generally regarded as monophyletic, and many analyses support the placement of arthropods with cycloneuralians (or their constituent clades) in a superphylum Ecdysozoa.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Overall, however, the basal relationships of animals are not yet well resolved.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Likewise, the relationships between various arthropod groups are still actively debated.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Today, arthropods contribute to the human food supply both directly as food and more importantly, indirectly as pollinators of crops.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Some species are known to spread severe disease to humans, livestock, and crops.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The word *arthropod* comes from the Greek ἄρθρον *árthron* 'joint', and πούς *poús* (gen. ποδός *podós*) 'foot' or 'leg', which together mean "jointed leg", with the word "arthropodes" initially used in anatomical descriptions by Barthélemy Charles Joseph Dumortier published in 1832.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The designation "Arthropoda" appears to have been first used in 1843 by the German zoologist Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst (1777–1857).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The origin of the name has been the subject of considerable confusion, with credit often given erroneously to Pierre André Latreille or Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold instead, among various others.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Terrestrial arthropods are often called bugs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods are invertebrates with segmented bodies and jointed limbs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton or cuticle consists of chitin, a polymer of N-Acetylglucosamine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The cuticle of many crustaceans, beetle mites, the clades Penetini and Archaeoglenini inside the beetle subfamily Phrenapatinae, and millipedes (except for bristly millipedes) is also biomineralized with calcium carbonate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Calcification of the endosternite, an internal structure used for muscle attachments, also occurs in some opiliones, and the pupal cuticle of the fly *Bactrocera dorsalis* contains calcium phosphate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropoda is the largest animal phylum, with the estimates of the number of arthropod species varying from 1,170,000 to 5~10 million and accounting for over 80 percent of all known living animal species.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] One arthropod sub-group, the insects, includes more described species than any other taxonomic class.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The total number of species remains difficult to determine, as estimates rely on census counts at specific locations, scaled up and projected onto other regions, then totalled – allowing for double-counting – to cover the whole world.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Modeling assumptions are involved at each stage, introducing uncertainty.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A study in 1992 estimated that there were 500,000 species of animals and plants in Costa Rica alone, of which 365,000 were arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] They are important members of marine, freshwater, land and air ecosystems and one of only two major animal groups that have adapted to life in dry environments; the other is amniotes, whose living members are reptiles, birds and mammals.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Both the smallest and largest arthropods are crustaceans.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The smallest belong to the class Tantulocarida, some of which are less than 100 micrometres (0.0039 in) long.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The largest are species in the class Malacostraca, with the legs of the Japanese spider crab potentially spanning up to 4 metres (13 ft) and the American lobster reaching weights over 20 kg (44 lbs).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The embryos of all arthropods are segmented, consisting of a series of repeated modules.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The last common ancestor of living arthropods probably consisted of a series of undifferentiated segments, each with a pair of appendages that functioned as limbs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, all known living and fossil arthropods have grouped segments into tagmata in which segments and their limbs are specialized in various ways.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The three-part appearance of many insect bodies and the two-part appearance of spiders is a result of this grouping.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] There are no external signs of segmentation in mites.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have two body elements that are not part of this serially repeated pattern of segments, an ocular somite at the front, where the mouth and eyes originated, and a telson at the rear, behind the anus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Originally, it seems that each appendage-bearing segment had two separate pairs of appendages: an upper, unsegmented exite and a lower, segmented endopod.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] These would later fuse into a single pair of biramous appendages united by a basal segment (protopod or basipod), with the upper branch acting as a gill while the lower branch was used for locomotion.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The appendages of most crustaceans and some extinct taxa such as trilobites have another segmented branch known as exopods, but whether these structures have a single origin remain controversial.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Alignment of anterior body segments and appendages across various arthropod taxa, based on the observations until the mid 2010s.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The most conspicuous specialization of segments is in the head.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Despite myriapods and hexapods both having similar head combinations, hexapods are deeply nested within crustacea while myriapods are not, so these traits are believed to have evolved separately.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In addition, some extinct arthropods, such as *Marrella*, belong to none of these groups, as their heads are formed by their own particular combinations of segments and specialized appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Working out the evolutionary stages by which all these different combinations could have appeared is so difficult that it has long been known as "The arthropod head problem".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Snodgrass even hoped it would not be solved, as he found trying to work out solutions to be fun.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropod exoskeletons are made of cuticle, a non-cellular material secreted by the epidermis.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The exocuticle and endocuticle together are known as the procuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Each body segment and limb section is encased in hardened cuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The joints between body segments and between limb sections are covered by flexible cuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The exoskeletons of most aquatic crustaceans are biomineralized with calcium carbonate extracted from the water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Some terrestrial crustaceans have developed means of storing the mineral, since on land they cannot rely on a steady supply of dissolved calcium carbonate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Biomineralization generally affects the exocuticle and the outer part of the endocuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The cuticle may have setae (bristles) growing from special cells in the epidermis.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Setae are as varied in form and function as appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton cannot stretch and thus restricts growth.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods, therefore, replace their exoskeletons by undergoing ecdysis (moulting), or shedding the old exoskeleton, the exuviae, after growing a new one that is not yet hardened.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Moulting cycles run nearly continuously until an arthropod reaches full size.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The developmental stages between each moult (ecdysis) until sexual maturity is reached is called an instar.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Differences between instars can often be seen in altered body proportions, colors, patterns, changes in the number of body segments or head width.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] After moulting, i.e. shedding their exoskeleton, the juvenile arthropods continue in their life cycle until they either pupate or moult again.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In the initial phase of moulting, the animal stops feeding and its epidermis releases moulting fluid, a mixture of enzymes that digests the endocuticle and thus detaches the old cuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] This phase begins when the epidermis has secreted a new epicuticle to protect it from the enzymes, and the epidermis secretes the new exocuticle while the old cuticle is detaching.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] When this stage is complete, the animal's body swells by taking in a large quantity of water or air, causing the old cuticle to split along predefined weaknesses where the old exocuticle was thinnest.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] It commonly takes several minutes for the animal to struggle out of the old cuticle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] At this point, the new one is wrinkled and so soft that the animal cannot support itself and finds it very difficult to move, and the new endocuticle has not yet formed.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The animal continues to pump itself up to stretch the new cuticle as much as possible, then hardens the new exocuticle and eliminates the excess air or water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] By the end of this phase, the new endocuticle has formed.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Many arthropods then eat the discarded cuticle to reclaim its materials.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Because arthropods are unprotected and nearly immobilized until the new cuticle has hardened, they are in danger both of being trapped in the old cuticle and of being attacked by predators.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Moulting may be responsible for 80 to 90% of all arthropod deaths.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropod bodies are also segmented internally, and the nervous, muscular, circulatory, and excretory systems have repeated components.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods come from a lineage of animals that have a coelom, a membrane-lined cavity between the gut and the body wall that accommodates the internal organs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The strong, segmented limbs of arthropods eliminate the need for one of the coelom's main ancestral functions, as a hydrostatic skeleton, which muscles compress in order to change the animal's shape and thus enable it to move.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Hence the coelom of the arthropod is reduced to small areas around the reproductive and excretory systems.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Its place is largely taken by a hemocoel, a cavity that runs most of the length of the body and through which blood flows.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have open circulatory systems.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Most have a few short, open-ended arteries.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In chelicerates and crustaceans, the blood carries oxygen to the tissues, while hexapods use a separate system of tracheae.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Many crustaceans and a few chelicerates and tracheates use respiratory pigments to assist oxygen transport.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The most common respiratory pigment in arthropods is copper-based hemocyanin; this is used by many crustaceans and a few centipedes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A few crustaceans and insects use iron-based haemoglobin, the respiratory pigment used by vertebrates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] As with other invertebrates, the respiratory pigments of those arthropods that have them are generally dissolved in the blood and rarely enclosed in corpuscles as they are in vertebrates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The heart is a muscular tube that runs just under the back and for most of the length of the hemocoel.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] It contracts in ripples that run from rear to front, pushing blood forwards.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Sections not being squeezed by the heart muscle are expanded either by elastic ligaments or by small muscles, in either case connecting the heart to the body wall.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Along the heart run a series of paired ostia, non-return valves that allow blood to enter the heart but prevent it from leaving before it reaches the front.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have a wide variety of respiratory systems.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Small species often do not have any, since their high ratio of surface area to volume enables simple diffusion through the body surface to supply enough oxygen.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Crustacea usually have gills that are modified appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Tracheae, systems of branching tunnels that run from the openings in the body walls, deliver oxygen directly to individual cells in many insects, myriapods and arachnids.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Living arthropods have paired main nerve cords running along their bodies below the gut, and in each segment the cords form a pair of ganglia from which sensory and motor nerves run to other parts of the segment.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Although the pairs of ganglia in each segment often appear physically fused, they are connected by commissures (relatively large bundles of nerves), which give arthropod nervous systems a characteristic ladder-like appearance.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The brain is in the head, encircling and mainly above the oesophagus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] It consists of the fused ganglia of the acron and one or two of the foremost segments that form the head – a total of three pairs of ganglia in most arthropods, but only two in chelicerates, which do not have antennae or the ganglion connected to them.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The ganglia of other head segments are often close to the brain and function as part of it.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In insects, these other head ganglia combine into a pair of subesophageal ganglia, under and behind the oesophagus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Spiders take this process a step further, as all the segmental ganglia are incorporated into the subesophageal ganglia, which occupy most of the space in the cephalothorax (front "super-segment").
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] There are two different types of arthropod excretory systems.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In aquatic arthropods, the end-product of biochemical reactions that metabolise nitrogen is ammonia, which is so toxic that it needs to be diluted as much as possible with water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The ammonia is then eliminated via any permeable membrane, mainly through the gills.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] All crustaceans use this system, and its high consumption of water may be responsible for the relative lack of success of crustaceans as land animals.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Most aquatic arthropods and some terrestrial ones also have organs called nephridia ("little kidneys"), which extract other wastes for excretion as urine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The stiff cuticles of arthropods would block out information about the outside world, except that they are penetrated by many sensors or connections from sensors to the nervous system.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In fact, arthropods have modified their cuticles into elaborate arrays of sensors.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Various touch sensors, mostly setae, respond to different levels of force, from strong contact to very weak air currents.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Chemical sensors provide equivalents of taste and smell, often by means of setae.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Pressure sensors often take the form of membranes that function as eardrums, but are connected directly to nerves rather than to auditory ossicles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The antennae of most hexapods include sensor packages that monitor humidity, moisture and temperature.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lack balance and acceleration sensors, and rely on their eyes to tell them which way is up.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The self-righting behaviour of cockroaches is triggered when pressure sensors on the underside of the feet report no pressure.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, many malacostracan crustaceans have statocysts, which provide the same sort of information as the balance and motion sensors of the vertebrate inner ear.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The proprioceptors of arthropods, sensors that report the force exerted by muscles and the degree of bending in the body and joints, are well understood.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, little is known about what other internal sensors arthropods may have.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods may have sophisticated visual systems that include one or more usually both of compound eyes and pigment-cup ocelli, ("little eyes").
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In most cases, ocelli are only capable of detecting the direction from which light is coming, using the shadow cast by the walls of the cup, although the main eyes of spiders are pigment-cup ocelli that are capable of forming images, and those of jumping spiders can rotate to track prey.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes consist of fifteen to several thousand independent ommatidia, columns that are usually hexagonal in cross section.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Each ommatidium is an independent sensor, with its own light-sensitive cells and often with its own lens and cornea.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes have a wide field of view, and can detect fast movement and, in some cases, the polarization of light.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] On the other hand, the relatively large size of ommatidia makes the images rather coarse, and compound eyes are shorter-sighted than those of birds and mammals – although this is not a severe disadvantage, as objects and events within 20 cm (8 in) are most important to most arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Several arthropods have colour vision, and that of some insects has been studied in detail; for example, the ommatidia of bees contain receptors for both green and ultra-violet.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A few arthropods, such as barnacles, are hermaphroditic, that is, each can have the organs of both sexes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, individuals of most species remain of one sex their entire lives.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A few species of insects and crustaceans can reproduce by parthenogenesis, especially if conditions favour a "population explosion".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, most arthropods rely on sexual reproduction, and parthenogenetic species often revert to sexual reproduction when conditions become less favourable.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The ability to undergo meiosis is widespread among arthropods including both those that reproduce sexually and those that reproduce parthenogenetically.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Although meiosis is a major characteristic of arthropods, understanding of its fundamental adaptive benefit has long been regarded as an unresolved problem, that appears to have remained unsettled.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Aquatic arthropods may breed by external fertilization, as for example horseshoe crabs do, or by internal fertilization, where the ova remain in the female's body and the sperm must somehow be inserted.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] All known terrestrial arthropods use internal fertilization.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Opiliones (harvestmen), millipedes, and some crustaceans use modified appendages such as gonopods or penises to transfer the sperm directly to the female.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, most male terrestrial arthropods produce spermatophores, waterproof packets of sperm, which the females take into their bodies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A few such species rely on females to find spermatophores that have already been deposited on the ground, but in most cases males only deposit spermatophores when complex courtship rituals look likely to be successful.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lay eggs, but scorpions are ovoviviparous: they produce live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother, and are noted for prolonged maternal care.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Newly born arthropods have diverse forms, and insects alone cover the range of extremes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Some hatch as apparently miniature adults (direct development), and in some cases, such as silverfish, the hatchlings do not feed and may be helpless until after their first moult.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Many insects (Holometabola) hatch as grubs or caterpillars, which do not have segmented limbs or hardened cuticles, and metamorphose into adult forms by entering an inactive phase in which the larval tissues are broken down and re-used to build the adult body.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Dragonfly larvae have the typical cuticles and jointed limbs of arthropods but are flightless water-breathers with extendable jaws.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Crustaceans commonly hatch as tiny nauplius larvae that have only three segments and pairs of appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Based on the distribution of shared plesiomorphic features in extant and fossil taxa, the last common ancestor of all arthropods is inferred to have been as a modular organism with each module covered by its own sclerite (armour plate) and bearing a pair of biramous limbs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, whether the ancestral limb was uniramous or biramous is far from a settled debate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] This Ur-arthropod had a ventral mouth, pre-oral antennae and dorsal eyes at the front of the body.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] It has been proposed that the Ediacaran animals *Parvancorina* and *Spriggina*, from around 555 million years ago, were arthropods, but later study shows that their affinities of being origin of arthropods are not reliable.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Small arthropods with bivalve-like shells have been found in Early Cambrian fossil beds dating 541 to 539 million years ago in China and Australia.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The earliest Cambrian trilobite fossils are about 520 million years old, but the class was already quite diverse and worldwide, suggesting that they had been around for quite some time.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In the Maotianshan shales, which date back to 518 million years ago, arthropods such as *Kylinxia* and *Erratus* have been found that seem to represent transitional fossils between stem (e.g.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Radiodonta such as *Anomalocaris*) and true arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Re-examination in the 1970s of the Burgess Shale fossils from about 505 million years ago identified many arthropods, some of which could not be assigned to any of the well-known groups, and thus intensified the debate about the Cambrian explosion.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A fossil of *Marrella* from the Burgess Shale has provided the earliest clear evidence of moulting.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The earliest fossil of likely pancrustacean larvae date from about 514 million years ago in the Cambrian, followed by unique taxa like *Yicaris* and *Wujicaris*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The purported pancrustacean/crustacean affinity of some cambrian arthropods (e.g.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Phosphatocopina, Bradoriida and Hymenocarine taxa like waptiids) were disputed by subsequent studies, as they might branch before the mandibulate crown-group.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Within the pancrustacean crown-group, only Malacostraca, Branchiopoda and Pentastomida have Cambrian fossil records.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Crustacean fossils are common from the Ordovician period onwards.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] They have remained almost entirely aquatic, possibly because they never developed excretory systems that conserve water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods provide the earliest identifiable fossils of land animals, from about 419 million years ago in the Late Silurian, and terrestrial tracks from about 450 million years ago appear to have been made by arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Arthropods possessed attributes that were easily coopted for life on land; their existing jointed exoskeletons provided protection against desiccation, support against gravity and a means of locomotion that was not dependent on water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Around the same time the aquatic, scorpion-like eurypterids became the largest ever arthropods, some as long as 2.5 m (8 ft 2 in).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The oldest known arachnid is the trigonotarbid *Palaeotarbus jerami*, from about 420 million years ago in the Silurian period.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] *Attercopus fimbriunguis*, from 386 million years ago in the Devonian period, bears the earliest known silk-producing spigots, but its lack of spinnerets means it was not one of the true spiders, which first appear in the Late Carboniferous over 299 million years ago.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The Jurassic and Cretaceous periods provide a large number of fossil spiders, including representatives of many modern families.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The oldest known scorpion is *Dolichophonus,* dated back to 436 million years ago.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Lots of Silurian and Devonian scorpions were previously thought to be gill-breathing, hence the idea that scorpions were primitively aquatic and evolved air-breathing book lungs later on.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However subsequent studies reveal most of them lacking reliable evidence for an aquatic lifestyle, while exceptional aquatic taxa (e.g.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] *Waeringoscorpio*) most likely derived from terrestrial scorpion ancestors.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The oldest fossil record of hexapod is obscure, as most of the candidates are poorly preserved and their hexapod affinities had been disputed.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] An iconic example is the Devonian *Rhyniognatha hirsti*, dated at 396 to 407 million years ago, its mandibles are thought to be a type found only in winged insects, which suggests that the earliest insects appeared in the Silurian period.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, later study shows that *Rhyniognatha* most likely represent a myriapod, not even a hexapod.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The unequivocal oldest known hexapod is the springtail *Rhyniella*, from about 410 million years ago in the Devonian period, and the palaeodictyopteran *Delitzschala bitterfeldensis*, from about 325 million years ago in the Carboniferous period, respectively.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The Mazon Creek lagerstätten from the Late Carboniferous, about 300 million years ago, include about 200 species, some gigantic by modern standards, and indicate that insects had occupied their main modern ecological niches as herbivores, detritivores and insectivores.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Social termites and ants first appear in the Early Cretaceous, and advanced social bees have been found in Late Cretaceous rocks but did not become abundant until the Middle Cenozoic.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] From 1952 to 1977, zoologist Sidnie Manton and others argued that arthropods are polyphyletic, in other words, that they do not share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Instead, they proposed that three separate groups of "arthropods" evolved separately from common worm-like ancestors: the chelicerates, including spiders and scorpions; the crustaceans; and the uniramia, consisting of onychophorans, myriapods and hexapods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] These arguments usually bypassed trilobites, as the evolutionary relationships of this class were unclear.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Further analysis and discoveries in the 1990s reversed this view, and led to acceptance that arthropods are monophyletic, in other words they are inferred to share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] These changes made the scope of the term "arthropod" unclear, and Claus Nielsen proposed that the wider group should be labelled "Panarthropoda" ("all the arthropods") while the animals with jointed limbs and hardened cuticles should be called "Euarthropoda" ("true arthropods").
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] A contrary view was presented in 2003, when Jan Bergström and Hou Xian-guang argued that, if arthropods were a "sister-group" to any of the anomalocarids, they must have lost and then re-evolved features that were well-developed in the anomalocarids.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The earliest known arthropods ate mud in order to extract food particles from it, and possessed variable numbers of segments with unspecialized appendages that functioned as both gills and legs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Anomalocarids were, by the standards of the time, huge and sophisticated predators with specialized mouths and grasping appendages, fixed numbers of segments some of which were specialized, tail fins, and gills that were very different from those of arthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In 2006, they suggested that arthropods were more closely related to lobopods and tardigrades than to anomalocarids.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In 2014, it was found that tardigrades were more closely related to arthropods than velvet worms.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Higher up the "family tree", the Annelida have traditionally been considered the closest relatives of the Panarthropoda, since both groups have segmented bodies, and the combination of these groups was labelled Articulata.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] There had been competing proposals that arthropods were closely related to other groups such as nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades, but these remained minority views because it was difficult to specify in detail the relationships between these groups.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In the 1990s, molecular phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences produced a coherent scheme showing arthropods as members of a superphylum labelled Ecdysozoa ("animals that moult"), which contained nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades but excluded annelids.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] This hypothesis groups annelids with molluscs and brachiopods in another superphylum, Lophotrochozoa.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] If the Ecdysozoa hypothesis is correct, then segmentation of arthropods and annelids either has evolved convergently or has been inherited from a much older ancestor and subsequently lost in several other lineages, such as the non-arthropod members of the Ecdysozoa.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] *Marrella* was the first one to be recognized as significantly different from the well-known groups.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The Deuteropoda is a recently established clade uniting the crown-group (living) arthropods with these possible "upper stem-group" fossils taxa.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The clade is defined by important changes to the structure of the head region such as the appearance of a differentiated deutocerebral appendage pair, which excludes more basal taxa like radiodonts and "gilled lobopodians".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Controversies remain about the positions of various extinct arthropod groups.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Some studies recover Megacheira as closely related to chelicerates, while others recover them as outside the group containing Chelicerate and Mandibulata as stem-group euarthropods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The placement of the Artiopoda (which contains the extinct trilobites and similar forms) is also a frequent subject of dispute.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The main hypotheses position them in the clade Arachnomorpha with the Chelicerates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] However, one of the newer hypotheses is that the chelicerae have originated from the same pair of appendages that evolved into antennae in the ancestors of Mandibulata, which would place trilobites, which had antennae, closer to Mandibulata than Chelicerata, in the clade Antennulata.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The fuxianhuiids, usually suggested to be stem-group arthropods, have been suggested to be Mandibulates in some recent studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The Hymenocarina, a group of bivalved arthropods, previously thought to have been stem-group members of the group, have been demonstrated to be mandibulates based on the presence of mandibles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] **Chelicerates** comprise the marine sea spiders and horseshoe crabs, along with the terrestrial arachnids such as mites, harvestmen, spiders, scorpions and related organisms characterized by the presence of chelicerae, appendages just above/in front of the mouthparts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Chelicerae appear in scorpions and horseshoe crabs as tiny claws that they use in feeding, but those of spiders have developed as fangs that inject venom.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] **Myriapods** comprise millipedes, centipedes, pauropods and symphylans, characterized by having numerous body segments each of which bearing one or two pairs of legs (or in a few cases being legless).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] All members are exclusively terrestrial.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] **Pancrustaceans** comprise ostracods, barnacles, copepods, malacostracans, cephalocaridans, branchiopods, remipedes and hexapods.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Most groups are primarily aquatic (two notable exceptions being woodlice and hexapods, which are both purely terrestrial) and are characterized by having biramous appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The most abundant group of pancrustaceans are the terrestrial hexapods, which comprise insects, diplurans, springtails, and proturans, with six thoracic legs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The phylogeny of the major extant arthropod groups has been an area of considerable interest and dispute.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] Recent studies strongly suggest that Crustacea, as traditionally defined, is paraphyletic, with Hexapoda having evolved from within it, so that Crustacea and Hexapoda form a clade, Pancrustacea.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] The position of Myriapoda, Chelicerata and Pancrustacea remains unclear as of April 2012.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p01] In some studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Chelicerata (forming Myriochelata); in other studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Pancrustacea (forming Mandibulata), or Myriapoda may be sister to Chelicerata plus Pancrustacea.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Crustaceans such as crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimp, and prawns have long been part of human cuisine, and are now raised commercially.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Insects and their grubs are at least as nutritious as meat, and are eaten both raw and cooked in many cultures, though not most European, Hindu, and Islamic cultures.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Cooked tarantulas are considered a delicacy in Cambodia, and by the Piaroa Indians of southern Venezuela, after the highly irritant hairs – the spider's main defence system – are removed.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Humans also unintentionally eat arthropods in other foods, and food safety regulations lay down acceptable contamination levels for different kinds of food material.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The intentional cultivation of arthropods and other small animals for human food, referred to as minilivestock, is now emerging in animal husbandry as an ecologically sound concept.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Commercial butterfly breeding provides Lepidoptera stock to butterfly conservatories, educational exhibits, schools, research facilities, and cultural events.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Besides pollinating, bees produce honey, which is the basis of a rapidly growing industry and international trade.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The red dye cochineal, produced from a Central American species of insect, was economically important to the Aztecs and Mayans.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] While the region was under Spanish control, it became Mexico's second most-lucrative export, and is now regaining some of the ground it lost to synthetic competitors.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Shellac, a resin secreted by a species of insect native to southern Asia, was historically used in great quantities for many applications in which it has mostly been replaced by synthetic resins, but it is still used in woodworking and as a food additive.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The blood of horseshoe crabs contains a clotting agent, limulus amebocyte lysate, which is now used to test that antibiotics and kidney machines are free of dangerous bacteria, and to detect spinal meningitis.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Forensic entomology uses evidence provided by arthropods to establish the time and sometimes the place of death of a human, and in some cases the cause.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Recently insects have also gained attention as potential sources of drugs and other medicinal substances.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The relative simplicity of the arthropods' body plan, allowing them to move on a variety of surfaces both on land and in water, have made them useful as models for robotics.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The redundancy provided by segments allows arthropods and biomimetic robots to move normally, even with damaged or lost appendages.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Although arthropods are the most numerous phylum on Earth, and thousands of arthropod species are venomous, they inflict relatively few serious bites and stings on humans.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Far more serious are the effects on humans of diseases like malaria carried by blood-sucking insects.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Other blood-sucking insects infect livestock with diseases that kill many animals and greatly reduce the usefulness of others.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Ticks can cause tick paralysis and several parasite-borne diseases in humans.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] A few of the closely related mites also infest humans, causing intense itching, and others cause allergic diseases, including hay fever, asthma, and eczema.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Many species of arthropods, principally insects but also mites, are agricultural and forest pests.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] The mite *Varroa destructor* has become the largest single problem faced by beekeepers worldwide.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Efforts to control arthropod pests by large-scale use of pesticides have caused long-term effects on human health and on biodiversity.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Increasing arthropod resistance to pesticides has led to the development of integrated pest management using a wide range of measures including biological control.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/arthropod-p02] Predatory mites may be useful in controlling some mite pests.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In addition to its Brunswick campus, Bowdoin owns a 118-acre (48 ha) coastal studies center on Orr's Island and a 200-acre (81 ha) scientific field station on Kent Island in the Bay of Fundy.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college was a founding member of its athletic conference, the New England Small College Athletic Conference, and the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Consortium, an athletic conference and inter-library exchange with Bates College and Colby College.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin has over 30 varsity teams, and the school mascot was selected as a polar bear in 1913 to honor Robert Peary, a Bowdoin alumnus who claimed to have led the first successful expedition to the North Pole.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College was chartered in 1794 by the Massachusetts State Legislature and was later redirected under the jurisdiction of the Maine Legislature.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] It was named for former Massachusetts governor James Bowdoin, whose son James Bowdoin III was an early benefactor.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin began to develop in the 1820s, a decade in which Maine became an independent state as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] President Franklin Pierce and two literary figures, Nathaniel Hawthorne and Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, both of whom graduated Phi Beta Kappa in 1825.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Pierce and Hawthorne began an official militia company called the 'Bowdoin Cadets'.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The Phi Beta Kappa Society was active at Bowdoin before the Civil War and featured anti-slavery speakers.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] From its founding, Bowdoin was known to educate the sons of the political elite and "catered very largely to the wealthy conservative from the state of Maine".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] During the first half of the 19th century, Bowdoin required of its students a certificate of "good moral character" as well as knowledge of Latin and Ancient Greek, geography, algebra, and the major works of Cicero, Xenophon, Virgil and Homer.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Harriet Beecher Stowe started writing her influential anti-slavery novel, *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, in Brunswick while her husband was teaching at the college.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Brigadier General (and Brevet Major General) Joshua Chamberlain, a Bowdoin alumnus and professor, was present at the surrender of the Army of Northern Virginia at Appomattox Court House in 1865.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Chamberlain, a Medal of Honor recipient who later served as governor of Maine and president of Bowdoin, fought at Gettysburg, where he commanded the 20th Maine in defense of Little Round Top.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Other notable Civil War-era alumni include Major General Oliver Otis Howard, class of 1850, who led the Freedmen's Bureau and later founded Howard University; Massachusetts Governor John Andrew, class of 1837, who was responsible for forming the 54th Massachusetts; and William P.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Fessenden (1823) and Hugh McCulloch (1827), both of whom served as Secretary of the Treasury during the Lincoln Administration.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] With strained relations over slavery between political parties, President Franklin Pierce appointed Jefferson Davis as his Secretary of War, and the college awarded the future President of the Confederacy an honorary degree.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The Jefferson Davis Award was established in 1972 following a donation from the United Daughters of the Confederacy and was given to students excelling in legal studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The award was discontinued in 2015, with the college president citing it as inappropriate because it honored someone "whose mission was to preserve and institutionalize slavery".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Although Bowdoin's Medical School of Maine closed in 1921, it produced notable graduates including Augustus Stinchfield, who received his M.D. in 1868 and became one of the co-founders of the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minnesota.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 1877, the college graduated Charles Morse, the American banker who established a near-monopoly of the ice business in New York, which contributed to the financial Panic of 1907.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college educated and graduated Arctic explorers Robert E.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Peary named Bowdoin Fjord and Bowdoin Glacier after his alma mater.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Peary led what he claimed was the first successful expedition to reach the North Pole in April 1909, and MacMillan, a member of Peary's crew, explored Greenland, Baffin Island, and Labrador in the schooner *Bowdoin* between 1908 and 1954.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] White, Jr., class of 1899, served as Senate Minority Leader from 1944 to 1947 and Senate Majority Leader from 1947 to 1949.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Mitchell, class of 1954, served as Senate Majority Leader from 1989 to 1995 before assuming an active role in the Northern Ireland peace process.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 1970, the college became one of a very limited number of liberal arts colleges to make the SAT optional in the admissions process.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 1971, after nearly 180 years as a men's college, Bowdoin admitted its first class of women.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Also in 1971, Bowdoin became a founding member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC) and began competing in the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Consortium with Bates College and Colby College.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The consortium became both an athletic rivalry and an academic exchange program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] On February 28, 1997, Bowdoin's Board of Trustees approved a plan to phase out fraternities on campus, replacing them with a system of college-owned social houses.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] On January 18, 2008, Bowdoin announced that it would eliminate loans for all students receiving financial aid, replacing those loans with grants beginning with the 2008–2009 academic year.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] President Barry Mills stated, "Some see a calling in such vital but often low-paying fields such as teaching or social work.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] With significant debt at graduation, some students will undoubtedly be forced to make career or education choices not based on their talents, interests, and promise in a particular field but rather on their capacity to repay student loans.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In February 2009, following a $10 million donation by Subway co-founder and alumnus Peter Buck, class of 1952, the college completed a $250 million capital campaign.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college also completed major construction projects on campus, including a renovation of the art museum and a new fitness center named after Peter Buck.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] On July 1, 2015, Clayton Rose succeeded Mills as president.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Eight years later, on July 1, 2023, Safa Zaki succeeded Rose as the first woman to serve as president of the college.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In February 2025, students occupied the Smith Union building to demand that the university divest from arms manufacturers, marking the first pro-Palestinian encampment during the second Trump administration.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The encampment followed Trump's comments on occupying Gaza and perceived inaction following an Israel divestment referendum passed by the student body a year prior.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The acceptance rate for the class of 2030 was 6.5%.The college received more than 14,727 applications for the class of 2030 – the highest application number in the college's history and a continuation of the rise in applications over the past four years.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Applications increased by about 50%, since the class of 2024 and about 100% since the class of 2021.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The April 17, 2008, edition of *The Economist* noted Bowdoin in an article on university admissions: "So-called 'almost-Ivies' such as Bowdoin and Middlebury also saw record low admission rates this year (18% each).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] It is now as hard to get into Bowdoin, says the college's admissions director, as it was to get into Princeton in the 1970s." Many students apply for financial aid, and around 85% of those who apply to receive aid.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin is a need-blind and no-loans institution.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] While a significant portion of the student body hails from New England—including nearly 25% from Massachusetts and 10% from Maine—recent classes have drawn from an increasingly national and international pool.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The median family income of Bowdoin students is $195,900, with 57% of students coming from the top 10% of highest-earning families and 17.5% from the bottom 60%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Although Bowdoin once had a reputation for homogeneity (both ethnically and socioeconomically), a diversity campaign has increased the percentage of students of color in recent classes to more than 31%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In fact, admission of minorities goes back at least as far as John Brown Russwurm 1826, Bowdoin's first Black college graduate and the third Black graduate of any American college.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Course distribution requirements were abolished in the 1970s but were reinstated by a faculty majority vote in 1981 due to an initiative by oral communication and film professor Barbara Kaster.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] She insisted that distribution requirements would ensure students a more well-rounded education in a diversity of fields and therefore present them with more career possibilities.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The requirements of at least two courses in each of the categories of Natural Sciences/mathematics, social and behavioral sciences, humanities/Fine Arts, and foreign studies (including languages) took effect for the class of 1987 and have been gradually amended since then.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Current requirements require one course each in natural sciences, quantitative reasoning, visual and performing arts, international perspectives, and difference, power, and inequity.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] A small writing-intensive course, called a first-year seminar, is also required.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 1990, the Bowdoin faculty voted to change the four-level grading system to the traditional A, B, C, D, and F system.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The previous system, consisting of high honors, honors, pass, and fail, was devised primarily to de-emphasize the importance of grades and to reduce competition.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 2002, the faculty decided to change the grading system to incorporate plus and minus grades.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 2006, Bowdoin was named a "Top Producer of Fulbright Awards for American Students" by the Institute of International Education.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Other notable Bowdoin faculty include (or have included): Edville Gerhardt Abbott, Charles Beitz, John Bisbee, Paul Chadbourne, Thomas Cornell, Kristen R.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Johnson, Richard Morgan, Elliott Schwartz, Kenneth Chenault, and Scott Sehon.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] News & World Report* rankings, Bowdoin was ranked tied at 5th best overall among liberal arts colleges in the United States, tied at 6th for "Best Undergraduate Teaching", 7th in "Best Value Schools", and tied at 30th for "Most Innovative Schools".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In the 2022 *Forbes* college rankings, Bowdoin was ranked 48th overall among 498 universities, liberal arts colleges, and service academies and 7th among private liberal arts colleges.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin was ranked first among 1,204 small colleges in the U.S. by Niche in 2017, but has since fallen to 6th.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Based on students' SAT scores, Bowdoin is tied with Williams for 5th in Business Insider's smartest liberal arts colleges, with an average score of 1435 for math and critical reading combined.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Among all colleges, it is tied with Brown, Carnegie Mellon, and Williams for 22nd.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college was ranked 5th in the country by *Washington Monthly* in 2019 based on its contribution to the public good, as measured by social mobility, research, and promoting public service.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 2006, *Newsweek* described Bowdoin as a "New Ivy", one of a number of liberal arts colleges and universities outside of the Ivy League, and it has also been dubbed a "Hidden Ivy".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's dining services have been ranked No.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin uses food from its organic garden in its two major dining halls, and every academic year begins with a lobster bake outside Farley Fieldhouse.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Recalling his days at Bowdoin in a 2005 interview, Professor Richard E.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Morgan (class of 1959) described student life at the then-all-male school as "monastic" and noted that "the only things to do were either work or drink".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] This is corroborated by the *Official Preppy Handbook,* which in 1980 ranked Bowdoin the number two drinking school in the country, behind Dartmouth.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Since abolishing Greek fraternities in the late 1990s, Bowdoin has switched to a system in which entering students are assigned a "college house" affiliation correlating with their first-year dormitory.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] While six houses were originally established following the construction of two new dorms, two were added effective in the fall of 2007, and one added in the fall of 2019, bringing the current total to eight: Baxter, Quinby, MacMillan, Howell, Helmreich, Reed, Burnett, and Boody-Johnson.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college houses are physical buildings around campus that host parties and other events throughout the year.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Those students who choose not to live in their affiliated house retain their affiliation and are considered members throughout their Bowdoin career.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The largest student group on campus is the Outing Club, which leads canoeing, kayaking, rafting, camping, and backpacking trips throughout Maine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] One of the school's two historic rival literary societies, The Peucinian Society, has recently been revitalized from its previous form.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The Peucinian Society was founded in 1805.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] This organization counts such people as Henry Wadsworth Longfellow and Joshua Lawrence Chamberlain among its former members.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The other, the now-defunct Athenian Society, included Nathaniel Hawthorne and Franklin Pierce as members.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin competes in the Standard Platform League of RoboCup as the Northern Bites, where teams compete with five autonomous Aldebaran Nao robots.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin won the world championship in RoboCup 2007, beating Carnegie Mellon University, and finished 2nd in the 2015 US Open.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's student newspaper, *The Bowdoin Orient*, is the oldest continuously published college weekly in the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The Orient was named the second-best tabloid-sized college weekly at a Collegiate Associated Press conference in March 2007 and the best college newspaper in New England by the New England Society of News Editors in 2018.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The school's literary magazine, *The Quill*, was published between 1897 and 2015.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] *The Bowdoin Globalist*, an international news, culture, and politics magazine affiliated with the Global21 organization of college magazines, has been publishing since 2012.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] *The Bowdoin Globalist* transitioned to a digital-only platform in 2015 and changed its name to *The Bowdoin Review*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college's radio station, WBOR, has been operating since the early 1940s.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 1999, *The Bowdoin Cable Network* was formed, producing a weekly newscast and several student-created shows per semester.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Six *a cappella* groups are on campus; the Meddiebempsters are the oldest.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Founded in the spring of 1937, the Meddies performed in USO shows after World War II.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College signed onto the American College and University President's Climate Commitment in 2007.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college followed through with a carbon neutrality plan released in 2009, with 2020 as the target year for carbon neutrality.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] According to the plan, general improvements to Maine's electricity grid will account for 7% of carbon reductions, commuting improvements will account for 1%, and the purchase of renewable energy credits will account for 41%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 2017, the college was on track to meet the 28% own source reduction target, and efforts have continued in the areas of energy conservation, efficiency upgrades and transitioning to lower carbon fuel sources.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin's facilities are heated by an on-campus heating plant that burns natural gas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Between 2002 and 2008, Bowdoin College decreased its CO2 emissions by 40%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] It achieved that reduction by switching from No.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] 2 oil in its heating plant, reducing the campus set heating point from 72 to 68 degrees, and by adhering to its own Green Design Standards in renovations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In addition, Bowdoin runs a single stream recycling program, and its dining services department has begun composting food waste and unbleached paper napkins.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin received an overall "B−" grade for its sustainability efforts on the College Sustainability Report Card 2009 published by the Sustainable Endowments Institute.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In 2003, Bowdoin committed to achieving LEED-certification for all new campus buildings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college has since completed construction on Osher and West residency halls, the Peter Buck Center for Health & Fitness, the Sidney J.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Watson Arena, 216 Maine Street, and 52 Harpswell all of which have attained LEED, Silver LEED or Gold LEED certification.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The new dorms partially use collected rainwater as part of an advanced flushing system.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The new Park Row Apartments and Schiller Coastal Studies Center are Passive House Certified through Phius.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College's main campus in Brunswick ranges over an area of 215 acres (87 ha) and includes 120 buildings, some of which date back to the 18th century.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Prominent buildings on the campus include the college's oldest building, Massachusetts Hall, the Parker Cleaveland House, and the Harriet Beecher Stowe House.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The campus has two museums: the Bowdoin College Museum of Art, in the Walker Art Building, and the Peary-MacMillan Arctic Museum, in the Gibbons Center for Arctic Studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The 118-acre (48 ha) Schiller Coastal Studies Center is located 8 miles (13 km) south of Orr's Island in Harpswell, Maine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College operates the Bowdoin Scientific Station on Kent Island in the Bay of Fundy in New Brunswick.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Organized athletics at Bowdoin began in 1828 with a gymnastics program established by the "father of athletics in Maine", John Neal.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] In the proceeding years, Neal agitated for more programs, and himself taught bowling, boxing, and other sports.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin College teams are known as the Polar Bears.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] They compete as a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division III level, primarily competing in the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC), of which they were a founding member in 1971.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The mascot for all Bowdoin College athletic teams is the Polar bear, generally referred to in the plural, i.e., "The Polar Bears".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The fight song, *Forward The White*, was composed by Kenneth A.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The college's rowing club competes in the Colby-Bates-Bowdoin Chase Regatta annually.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The rowing club also competes as a member of the American Collegiate Rowing Association; the women's team won its first national championship in 2023.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The field hockey team are four-time NCAA Division III National Champions; winning the title in 2007 (defeating Middlebury College), 2008 (defeating Tufts University), 2010 (defeating Messiah College), and 2013 (defeating Salisbury University).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] The men's tennis team won the 2016 NCAA Division III Championship after defeating Emory University in Kalamazoo, Michigan.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Principal athletic facilities include Whittier Field (capacity: 9,000), Morrell Gymnasium (1,500), Sidney J.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Watson Arena (2,300), Pickard Fields, and the Buck Center for Health and Wellness.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Bowdoin graduates have led all three branches of the American federal government, including both houses of Congress.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Franklin Pierce (1824) was America's fourteenth President; Melville Weston Fuller (1853) served as Chief Justice of the United States; Thomas Brackett Reed (1860) was twice elected Speaker of the House of Representatives; and Wallace H.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/bowdoin-college] Mitchell (1954) both served as Majority Leader of the United States Senate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university is home to the oldest applied mathematics program in the country and oldest engineering program in the Ivy League.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] It was one of the early doctoral-granting institutions in the U.S., adding masters and doctoral studies in 1887.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1969, it adopted its Open Curriculum after student lobbying, which eliminated mandatory general education distribution requirements.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1971, Brown's coordinate women's institution, Pembroke College, was fully merged into the university.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university comprises the College, the Graduate School, Alpert Medical School, the School of Engineering, the School of Public Health and the School of Professional Studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Its international programs are organized through the Watson School of International and Public Affairs, and it is academically affiliated with the Marine Biological Laboratory and the Rhode Island School of Design, which offers undergraduate and graduate dual degree programs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university is surrounded by a federally listed architectural district with a concentration of colonial-era buildings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Benefit Street has one of America's richest concentrations of 18th- and 19th-century architecture.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Undergraduate admissions are among the most selective in the country, with an acceptance rate of 5% for the class of 2026.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] As of October 2025, 12 Nobel Prize winners, 1 Fields Medalist, 7 National Humanities Medalists, and 11 National Medal of Science laureates have been affiliated with Brown as alumni, faculty, or researchers.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Alumni also include 29 Pulitzer Prize winners, 21 billionaires, 4 U.S. secretaries of state, over 100 members of the United States Congress, 58 Rhodes Scholars, 22 MacArthur Genius Fellows, and 38 Olympic medalists.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The three petitioners were Ezra Stiles, pastor of Newport's Second Congregational Church and future president of Yale University; William Ellery Jr., future signer of the United States Declaration of Independence; and Josias Lyndon, future governor of the colony.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Stiles and Ellery later served as co-authors of the college's charter two years later.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The editor of Stiles's papers observes, "This draft of a petition connects itself with other evidence of Dr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Philadelphia Baptist Association was also interested in establishing a college in Rhode Island, which was founded as a Baptist colony in America, including the mother-church of all American Baptists: the First Baptist Church in America.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The local University of Pennsylvania in their native Philadelphia was founded by Benjamin Franklin without direct association with any particular denomination.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] James Manning arrived at Newport in July 1763 and was introduced to Stiles, who agreed to write the charter for the college.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Stiles' first draft was read to the General Assembly in August 1763, and rejected by Baptist members who worried that their denomination would be underrepresented in the College Board of Fellows.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A revised charter written by Stiles and Ellery was adopted by the Rhode Island General Assembly on March 3, 1764, in East Greenwich.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In September 1764, the inaugural meeting of the corporation—the college's governing body—was held in Newport's Old Colony House.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Governor Stephen Hopkins was chosen chancellor, former and future governor Samuel Ward vice chancellor, John Tillinghast treasurer, and Thomas Eyres secretary.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The charter stipulated that the board of trustees should be composed of 22 Baptists, 5 Quakers, 5 Episcopalians, and 4 Congregationalists.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] At the time of its creation, Brown's charter was a uniquely progressive document.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The college was founded as Rhode Island College, at the site of the First Baptist Church in Warren, Rhode Island.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Manning was sworn in as the college's first president in 1765 and remained in the role until 1791.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1766, the college authorized Morgan Edwards to travel to Europe to "solicit Benefactions for this Institution".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] During his year-and-a-half stay in the British Isles, Edwards secured funding from benefactors including Thomas Penn and Benjamin Franklin.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1770, the college moved from Warren to Providence.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] To establish a campus, John and Moses Brown purchased a four-acre lot on the crest of College Hill on behalf of the school.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The majority of the property fell within the bounds of the original home lot of Chad Brown, an ancestor of the Browns and one of the original proprietors of Providence Plantations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] After the college was relocated to the city, work began on constructing its first building.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A building committee, organized by the corporation, developed plans for the college's first purpose-built edifice, finalizing a design on February 9, 1770.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The subsequent structure, referred to as "The College Edifice" and later as University Hall, may have been modeled on Nassau Hall, built 14 years prior at the College of New Jersey.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] President Manning, an active member of the building process, was educated at Princeton and might have suggested that Brown's first building resemble that of his alma mater.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Nicholas Brown, John Brown, Joseph Brown, and Moses Brown were instrumental in moving the college to Providence, constructing its first building, and securing its endowment.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Joseph became a professor of natural philosophy at the college; John served as its treasurer from 1775 to 1796; and Nicholas Sr's son Nicholas Brown Jr. succeeded his uncle as treasurer from 1796 to 1825.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] On September 8, 1803, the corporation voted, "That the donation of $5,000, if made to this College within one Year from the late Commencement, shall entitle the donor to name the College." The following year, the appeal was answered by College Treasurer Nicholas Brown Jr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1904, the John Carter Brown Library was established as an independently funded research library on Brown's campus; the library's collection was founded on that of John Carter Brown, son of Nicholas Brown Jr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Brown family was involved in various business ventures in Rhode Island, and accrued wealth both directly and indirectly from the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The family was divided on the issue of slavery.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] John Brown had defended slavery, while Moses and Nicholas Brown Jr. were fervent abolitionists.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 2003, under the tenure of President Ruth Simmons, who was the first African-American president of an Ivy League institution, the university established a steering committee to investigate these ties of the university to slavery and recommend a strategy to address them.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] With British vessels patrolling Narragansett Bay in the fall of 1776, the college library was moved out of Providence for safekeeping.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] This has been celebrated as marking the defeat of the British and the end of the war.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The building functioned as barracks and hospital from December 10, 1776, to April 20, 1780, and as a hospital for French troops from June 26, 1780, to May 27, 1782.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A number of Brown's founders and alumni played roles in the American Revolution and subsequent founding of the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's first chancellor, Stephen Hopkins, served as a delegate to the Colonial Congress in Albany in 1754, and to the Continental Congress from 1774 to 1776.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] James Manning represented Rhode Island at the Congress of the Confederation, while concurrently serving as Brown's first president.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Two of Brown's founders, William Ellery and Stephen Hopkins signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] James Mitchell Varnum, who graduated from Brown with honors in 1769, served as one of General George Washington's Continental Army brigadier generals and later as major general in command of the entire Rhode Island militia.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Varnum is noted as the founder and commander of the 1st Rhode Island Regiment, widely regarded as the first Black battalion in U.S. military history.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] David Howell, who graduated with an A.M. in 1769, served as a delegate to the Continental Congress from 1782 to 1785.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] , was the first alum to serve as president.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] , urged American universities to adopt a broader curriculum.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Nineteen individuals have served as presidents of the university since its founding in 1764.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Since 2012, Christina Hull Paxson has served as president.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Paxson had previously served as dean of Princeton University's School of Public and International Affairs and chair of Princeton's economics department.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Paxson's immediate predecessor, Ruth Simmons, is noted as the first African American president of an Ivy League institution.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Other presidents of note include academic, Vartan Gregorian; and philosopher and economist, Francis Wayland.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1966, the first Group Independent Study Project (GISP) at Brown was formed, involving 80 students and 15 professors.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The GISP was inspired by student-initiated experimental schools, especially San Francisco State College, and sought ways to "put students at the center of their education" and "teach students how to think rather than just teaching facts".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The following year Magaziner began organizing the student body to press for the reforms, organizing discussions and protests.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1968, university president Ray Heffner established a Special Committee on Curricular Philosophy.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Composed of administrators, the committee was tasked with developing specific reforms and producing recommendations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A report, produced by the committee, was presented to the faculty, which voted the New Curriculum into existence on May 7, 1969.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Modes of Thought course was discontinued early on, but the other elements remain in place.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 2006, the reintroduction of plus/minus grading was proposed in response to concerns regarding grade inflation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The idea was rejected by the College Curriculum Council after canvassing alumni, faculty, and students, including the original authors of the Magaziner-Maxwell Report.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 2003, then-university president Ruth Simmons launched a steering committee to research Brown's eighteenth-century ties to slavery.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In October 2006, the committee released a report documenting its findings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Titled "Slavery and Justice", the document detailed the ways in which the university benefited both directly and indirectly from the transatlantic slave trade and the labor of enslaved people.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The report also included seven recommendations for how the university should address this legacy.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown has since completed a number of these recommendations including the establishment of its Center for the Study of Slavery and Justice, the construction of its *Slavery Memorial*, and the funding of a $10 million permanent endowment for Providence Public Schools.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The "Slavery and Justice" report marked the first major effort by an American university to address its ties to slavery and prompted other institutions to undertake similar processes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] On July 30, 2025, Brown struck a deal with the Trump administration to restore federal research grant funding, after the administration froze it due to complaints mainly about antisemitism on the campus in the wake of pro-Palestinian protests.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] This deal included $50 million to be paid over ten years to state workforce development programs, a vow to exclude transgender women from women's spaces, a commitment to combatting antisemitism, and renewed partnership with Israeli institutions, among other items.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] This is the third settlement of its kind from a university to the administration, following Columbia University and the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Following the federal government's offer of compliance with increased restrictions in exchange for preferential treatment in funding decisions, the university's leaders solicited comments from the university community.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Once the period for comments concluded, they chose to reject the offer, becoming the second university to do so after Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] On December 13, 2025, a mass shooting occurred in the Barus and Holley Engineering Building, killing two and injuring nine more.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's coat of arms was created in 1834.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The prior year, president Francis Wayland had commissioned a committee to update the school's original seal to match the name the university had adopted in 1804.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Central in the coat of arms is a white escutcheon divided into four sectors by a red cross.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Within each sector of the coat of arms lies an open book.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Above the shield is a crest consisting of the upper half of a sun in splendor among the clouds atop a red and white torse.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Soldiers Memorial Gate (1921) long marked the eastern edge of Brown's campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown is the largest institutional landowner in Providence, with properties on College Hill and in the Jewelry District.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university was built contemporaneously with the eighteenth and nineteenth-century precincts surrounding it, making Brown's campus tightly integrated into Providence's urban fabric.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Among the noted architects who have shaped Brown's campus are McKim, Mead & White, Philip Johnson, Rafael Viñoly, Diller Scofidio + Renfro, and Robert A.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's main campus, comprises 235 buildings and 143 acres (58 ha) in the East Side neighborhood of College Hill.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university's central campus sits on a 15-acre (6.1 ha) block bounded by Waterman, Prospect, George, and Thayer Streets; newer buildings extend northward, eastward, and southward.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's core, historic campus, constructed primarily between 1770 and 1926, is defined by three greens: the Front or Quiet Green, the Main or College Green, and the Ruth J.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Simmons Quadrangle (historically known as Lincoln Field).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A brick and wrought-iron fence punctuated by decorative gates and arches traces the block's perimeter.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] This section of campus is primarily Georgian and Richardsonian Romanesque in its architectural character.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] To the south of the central campus are academic buildings and residential quadrangles, including Wriston, Keeney, and Gregorian quadrangles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Immediately to the east of the campus core sit Sciences Park and Brown's School of Engineering.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] North of the central campus are performing and visual arts facilities, life sciences labs, and the Pembroke Campus, which houses both dormitories and academic buildings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Facing the western edge of the central campus sit two of the Brown's seven libraries, the John Hay Library and the John D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The university's campus is contiguous with that of the Rhode Island School of Design, which is located immediately to Brown's west, along the slope of College Hill.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Built in 1901, the Van Wickle Gates are a set of wrought iron gates that stand at the western edge of Brown's campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The larger main gate is flanked by two smaller side gates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] At Convocation the central gate opens inward to admit the procession of new students; at Commencement, the gate opens outward for the procession of graduates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] A Brown superstition holds that students who walk through the central gate a second time prematurely will not graduate, although walking backward is said to cancel the hex.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The John Hay Library is the second oldest library on campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Opened in 1910, the library is named for John Hay (class of 1858), private secretary to Abraham Lincoln and Secretary of State under William McKinley and Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The construction of the building was funded in large part by Hay's friend, Andrew Carnegie, who contributed half of the $300,000 cost of construction.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The John Hay Library serves as the repository of the university's archives, rare books and manuscripts, and special collections.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Noteworthy among the latter are the Anne S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Hay Library is home to one of the broadest collections of incunabula in the Americas, one of Brown's two Shakespeare First Folios, the manuscript of George Orwell's *Nineteen Eighty-Four,* and three books bound in human skin.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Founded in 1846, the John Carter Brown Library is generally regarded as the world's leading collection of primary historical sources relating to the exploration and colonization of the Americas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] While administered and funded separately from the university, the library has been owned by Brown and located on its campus since 1904.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The library contains the best preserved of the eleven surviving copies of the Bay Psalm Book—the earliest extant book printed in British North America and the most expensive printed book in the world.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Other holdings include a Shakespeare First Folio and the world's largest collection of 16th-century Mexican texts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The exhibition galleries of the Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology, Brown's teaching museum, are located in Manning Hall on the campus's main green.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Its one million artifacts, available for research and educational purposes, are located at its Collections Research Center in Bristol, Rhode Island.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The museum's goal is to inspire creative and critical thinking about culture by fostering an interdisciplinary understanding of the material world.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] It provides opportunities for faculty and students to work with collections and the public, teaching through objects and programs in classrooms and exhibitions.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The museum sponsors lectures and events in all areas of anthropology and also runs an extensive program of outreach to local schools.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Annmary Brown Memorial was constructed from 1903 to 1907 by the politician, Civil War veteran, and book collector General Rush Hawkins, as a mausoleum for his wife, Annmary Brown, a member of the Brown family.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In addition to its crypt—the final repository for Brown and Hawkins—the Memorial includes works of art from Hawkins's private collection, including paintings by Angelica Kauffman, Peter Paul Rubens, Gilbert Stuart, Giovanni Battista Tiepolo, Benjamin West, and Eastman Johnson, among others.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] His collection of over 450 incunabula was relocated to the John Hay Library in 1990.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Today the Memorial is home to Brown's Medieval Studies and Renaissance Studies programs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Walk, a landscaped pedestrian corridor, connects the Pembroke Campus to the main campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] It runs parallel to Thayer Street and serves as a primary axis of campus, extending from Ruth Simmons Quadrangle at its southern terminus to the Meeting Street entrance to the Pembroke Campus at its northern end.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The corridor is home to public art including sculptures by Maya Lin and Tom Friedman.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Women's College in Brown University, known as Pembroke College, was founded in October 1891.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Upon its 1971 merger with the College of Brown University, Pembroke's campus was absorbed into the larger Brown campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The Pembroke campus is bordered by Meeting, Brown, Bowen, and Thayer Streets and sits three blocks north of Brown's central campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The campus is dominated by brick architecture, largely of the Georgian and Victorian styles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The west side of the quadrangle comprises Pembroke Hall (1897), Smith-Buonanno Hall (1907), and Metcalf Hall (1919), while the east side comprises Alumnae Hall (1927) and Miller Hall (1910).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The quadrangle culminates on the north with Andrews Hall (1947).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] East Campus, centered on Hope and Charlesfield streets, originally served as the campus of Bryant University.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1969, as Bryant was preparing to relocate to Smithfield, Rhode Island, Brown purchased their Providence campus for $5 million.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] The transaction expanded the Brown campus by 10 acres (40,000 m2) and 26 buildings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 1971, Brown renamed the area East Campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Today, the area is largely used for dormitories.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Thayer Street runs through Brown's main campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] As a commercial corridor frequented by students, Thayer is comparable to Harvard Square or Berkeley's Telegraph Avenue.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Wickenden Street, in the adjacent Fox Point neighborhood, is another commercial street similarly popular among students.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Built in 1925, Brown Stadium—the home of the school's football team—is located approximately a mile and a half northeast of the university's central campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Marston Boathouse, the home of Brown's crew teams, lies on the Seekonk River, to the southeast of campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's sailing teams are based out of the Ted Turner Sailing Pavilion at the Edgewood Yacht Club in adjacent Cranston.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Since 2011, Brown's Warren Alpert Medical School has been located in Providence's historic Jewelry District, near the medical campus of Brown's teaching hospitals, Rhode Island Hospital and the Women and Infants Hospital of Rhode Island.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Other university facilities, including molecular medicine labs and administrative offices, are likewise located in the area.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's School of Public Health occupies a landmark modernist building along the Providence River.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Other Brown properties include the 376-acre (1.52 km2) Mount Hope Grant in Bristol, Rhode Island, an important Native American site noted as a location of King Philip's War.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown's Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology Collection Research Center, particularly strong in Native American items, is located in the Mount Hope Grant.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown has committed to "minimize its energy use, reduce negative environmental impacts, and promote environmental stewardship." Since 2010, the university has required all new buildings meet LEED silver standards.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Between 2007 and 2018, Brown reduced its greenhouse gas emissions by 27 percent; the majority of this reduction is attributable to the university's Thermal Efficiency Project which converted its central heating plant from a steam-powered system to a hot water-powered system.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 2020, Brown announced it had sold 90 percent of its fossil fuel investments as part of a broader divestment from direct investments and managed funds that focus on fossil fuels.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] In 2021, the university adopted the goal of reducing quantifiable campus emissions by 75 percent by 2025 and achieving carbon neutrality by 2040.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Brown is a member of the Ivy Plus Sustainability Consortium, through which it has committed to best-practice sharing and the ongoing exchange of campus sustainability solutions along with other member institutions.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p01] Kuchler U.S. potential natural vegetation types, Brown would have a dominant vegetation type of Appalachian Oak (*104*) with a dominant vegetation form of Eastern Hardwood Forest (*25*).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Founded in 1764, the College is Brown's oldest school.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] About 7,200 undergraduate students are enrolled in the college, and 81 concentrations are offered.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] For the graduating class of 2020, the most popular concentrations were Computer Science, Economics, Biology, History, Applied Mathematics, International Relations, and Political Science.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] A quarter of Brown undergraduates complete more than one concentration before graduating.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] If the existing programs do not align with their intended curricular interests, undergraduates may design and pursue independent concentrations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Around 35 percent of undergraduates pursue graduate or professional study immediately, 60 percent within 5 years, and 80 percent within 10 years.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] For the Class of 2009, 56 percent of all undergraduate alumni have since earned graduate degrees.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Among undergraduate alumni who go on to receive graduate degrees, the most common degrees earned are J.D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The most common institutions from which undergraduate alumni earn graduate degrees are Brown University, Columbia University, and Harvard University.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The highest fields of employment for undergraduate alumni ten years after graduation are education and higher education (15%), medicine (9%), business and finance (9%), law (8%), and computing and technology (7%).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since its 1893 relocation to College Hill, Rhode Island School of Design (RISD) has bordered Brown to its west.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since 1900, Brown and RISD students have been able to cross-register at the two institutions, with Brown students permitted to take as many as four courses at RISD to count towards their Brown degree.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The two institutions partner to provide various student-life services and the two student bodies compose a synergy in the College Hill cultural scene.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] After several years of discussion between the two institutions and several students pursuing dual degrees unofficially, Brown and RISD formally established a five-year dual degree program in 2007, with the first class matriculating in the fall of 2008.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Brown|RISD Dual Degree Program, among the most selective in the country, offered admission to 20 of the 725 applicants for the class entering in autumn 2020, for an acceptance rate of 2.7%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The program combines the complementary strengths of the two institutions, integrating studio art and design at RISD with Brown's academic offerings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Students are admitted to the dual degree program for a course lasting five years and culminating in both the Bachelor of Arts (A.B.) or Bachelor of Science (Sc.B.) degree from Brown and the Bachelor of Fine Arts (B.F.A.) degree from RISD.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Prospective students must apply to the two schools separately and be accepted by separate admissions committees.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Their application must then be approved by a third Brown|RISD joint committee.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Admitted students spend the first year in residence at RISD completing its first-year Experimental and Foundation Studies curriculum while taking up to three Brown classes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Students spend their second year in residence at Brown, during which students take mainly Brown courses while starting on their RISD major requirements.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In the third, fourth, and fifth years, students can elect to live at either school or off-campus, and course distribution is determined by the requirements of each student's unique combination of Brown concentration and RISD major.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Program participants are noted for their creative and original approach to cross-disciplinary opportunities, combining, for example, industrial design with engineering, or anatomical illustration with human biology, or philosophy with sculpture, or architecture with urban studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] An annual "BRDD Exhibition" is a well-publicized and heavily attended event, drawing interest and attendees from the broader world of industry, design, the media, and the fine arts.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2020, the two schools announced the establishment of a new joint Master of Arts in Design Engineering program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Abbreviated as MADE, the program intends to combine RISD's programs in industrial design with Brown's programs in engineering.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The program is administered through Brown's School of Engineering and RISD's Architecture and Design Division.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's theatre and playwriting programs are among the best-regarded in the country.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Six Brown graduates have received the Pulitzer Prize for Drama; Alfred Uhry '58, Lynn Nottage '86, Ayad Akhtar '93, Nilo Cruz '94, Quiara Alegría Hudes '04, and Jackie Sibblies Drury MFA '04.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In *American Theater* magazine's 2009 ranking of the most-produced American plays, Brown graduates occupied four of the top five places—Peter Nachtrieb '97, Rachel Sheinkin '89, Sarah Ruhl '97, and Stephen Karam '02.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The undergraduate concentration encompasses programs in theatre history, performance theory, playwriting, dramaturgy, acting, directing, dance, speech, and technical production.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Applications for doctoral and master's degree programs are made through the University Graduate School.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Master's degrees in acting and directing are pursued in conjunction with the Brown/Trinity Rep MFA program, which partners with the Trinity Repertory Company, a local regional theatre.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In January 2025, The Brown/Trinity Rep Master of Fine Arts Programs in Acting and Directing indefinitely paused its new student admissions, effectively ending the program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Writing at Brown—fiction, non-fiction, poetry, playwriting, screenwriting, electronic writing, mixed media, and the undergraduate writing proficiency requirement—is catered for by various centers and degree programs, and a faculty that has long included nationally and internationally known authors.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The undergraduate concentration in literary arts offers courses in fiction, poetry, screenwriting, literary hypermedia, and translation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Graduate programs include the fiction and poetry MFA writing programs in the literary arts department and the MFA playwriting program in the theatre arts and performance studies department.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The non-fiction writing program is offered in the English department.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Screenwriting and cinema narrativity courses are offered in the departments of literary arts and modern culture and media.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The undergraduate writing proficiency requirement is supported by the Writing Center.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Alumni authors take their degrees across the spectrum of degree concentrations, but a gauge of the strength of writing at Brown is the number of major national writing prizes won.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Rubin '80 (2016); Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction-winner James Forman Jr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown began offering computer science courses through the departments of Economics and Applied Mathematics in 1956 when it acquired an IBM machine.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown added an IBM 650 in January 1958, the only one of its type between Hartford and Boston.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 1960, Brown opened its first dedicated computer building, the Brown University Computing Laboratory.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The facility, designed by Philip Johnson, received an IBM 7070 computer the following year.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The first undergraduate Computer Science degrees were awarded in 1974.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown granted computer sciences full Departmental status in 1979.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2009, IBM and Brown announced the installation of a supercomputer (by teraflops standards), the most powerful in the southeastern New England region.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In the 1960s, Andries van Dam, along with Ted Nelson and Bob Wallace invented The Hypertext Editing Systems, HES and FRESS while at Brown.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Nelson coined the word *hypertext* while Van Dam's students helped originate XML, XSLT, and related Web standards.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Among the school's computer science alumni are principal architect of the Classic Mac OS, Andy Hertzfeld; principal architect of the Intel 80386 and Intel 80486 microprocessors, John Crawford; former CEO of Apple, John Sculley; and digital effects programmer Masi Oka.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Lazowska, professor and Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation Chair emeritus at the University of Washington.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Between 2012 and 2018, the number of concentrators in CS tripled.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2017, computer science overtook economics as the school's most popular undergraduate concentration.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's program in applied mathematics was established in 1941 making it the oldest such program in the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The division is highly ranked and regarded nationally.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Among the 67 recipients of the Timoshenko Medal, 22 have been affiliated with Brown's applied mathematics division as faculty, researchers, or students.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Department of Egyptology and Assyriology in Wilbour Hall (1888).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Established in 2004, the Joukowsky Institute for Archaeology and the Ancient World is Brown's interdisciplinary research center for archeology and ancient studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute pursues fieldwork, excavations, regional surveys, and academic study of the archaeology and art of the ancient Mediterranean, Egypt, and Western Asia from the Levant to the Caucasus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute has a very active fieldwork profile, with faculty-led excavations and regional surveys presently in Petra (Jordan), Abydos (Egypt), Turkey, Sudan, Italy, Mexico, Guatemala, Montserrat, and Providence.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Joukowsky Institute's faculty includes cross-appointments from the departments of Egyptology, Assyriology, Classics, Anthropology, and History of Art and Architecture.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Faculty research and publication areas include Greek and Roman art and architecture, landscape archaeology, urban and religious architecture of the Levant, Roman provincial studies, the Aegean Bronze Age, and the archaeology of the Caucasus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute offers visiting teaching appointments and postdoctoral fellowships which have, in recent years, included Near Eastern Archaeology and Art, Classical Archaeology and Art, Islamic Archaeology and Art, and Archaeology and Media Studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Facing the Joukowsky Institute, across the Front Green, is the Department of Egyptology and Assyriology, formed in 2006 by the merger of Brown's departments of Egyptology and History of Mathematics.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] It is one of only a handful of such departments in the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The curricular focus is on three principal areas: Egyptology, Assyriology, and the history of the ancient exact sciences (astronomy, astrology, and mathematics).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Many courses in the department are open to all Brown undergraduates without prerequisites and include archaeology, languages, history, and Egyptian and Mesopotamian religions, literature, and science.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Students concentrating in the department choose a track of either Egyptology or Assyriology.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Graduate-level study comprises three tracks to the doctoral degree: Egyptology, Assyriology, or the History of the Exact Sciences in Antiquity.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Watson Institute for International and Public Affairs, Brown's center for the study of global Issues and public affairs, is one of the leading institutes of its type in the country.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute occupies facilities designed by Uruguayan architect Rafael Viñoly and Japanese architect Toshiko Mori.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute was initially endowed by Thomas Watson Jr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] (Class of 1937), former Ambassador to the Soviet Union and longtime president of IBM.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute's curricular interest is organized into the principal themes of development, security, and governance—with further focuses on globalization, economic uncertainty, security threats, environmental degradation, and poverty.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Six Brown undergraduate concentrations are hosted by the Watson Institute: Development Studies, International and Public Affairs, International Relations, Latin American and Caribbean Studies, Middle East Studies, Public Policy, and South Asian Studies.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Graduate programs offered at the Watson Institute include the Graduate Program in Development (Ph.D.) and the Master of Public Affairs (M.P.A) Program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute also offers postdoctoral, professional development, and global outreach programming.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In support of these programs, the institute houses various centers, including the Brazil Initiative, Brown-India Initiative, China Initiative, Middle East Studies Center, The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies (CLACS), and the Taubman Center for Public Policy.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In recent years, the most internationally cited product of the Watson Institute has been its Costs of War Project, first released in 2011 and continuously updated since.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The project comprises a team of economists, anthropologists, political scientists, legal experts, and physicians, and seeks to calculate the economic costs, human casualties, and impact on civil liberties of the wars in Iraq, Afghanistan, and Pakistan since 2001.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Established in 1847, Brown's engineering program is the oldest in the Ivy League and the third oldest civilian engineering program in the country.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 1916, Brown's departments of electrical, mechanical, and civil engineering were merged into a single Division of Engineering.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2010 the division was elevated to a School of Engineering.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Engineering at Brown is especially interdisciplinary.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The school is organized without the traditional departments or boundaries found at most schools and follows a model of connectivity between disciplines—including biology, medicine, physics, chemistry, computer science, the humanities, and the social sciences.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The school practices an innovative clustering of faculties in which engineers team with non-engineers to bring a convergence of ideas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Student teams have launched two CubeSats with the support of the School of Engineering.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown Space Engineering developed EQUiSat a 1U satellite, and another interdisciplinary team developed SBUDNIC a 3U satellite.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since 2009, Brown has developed an Executive MBA program in conjunction with one of the leading Business Schools in Europe, IE Business School in Madrid.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] This relationship has since strengthened resulting in both institutions offering a dual degree program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In this partnership, Brown provides its traditional coursework while IE provides most of the business-related subjects making a differentiated alternative program to other Ivy League's EMBAs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The cohort typically consists of 25–30 EMBA candidates from some 20 countries.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Classes are held in Providence, Madrid, Cape Town and Online.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Pembroke Center for Teaching and Research on Women was established at Brown in 1981 by Joan Wallach Scott as an interdisciplinary research center on gender.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The center is named for Pembroke College, Brown's former women's college, and is affiliated with Brown's Sarah Doyle Women's Center.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Pembroke Center supports Brown's undergraduate concentration in Gender and Sexuality Studies, post-doctoral research fellowships, the annual Pembroke Seminar, and other academic programs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] It also manages various collections, archives, and resources, including the Elizabeth Weed Feminist Theory Papers and the Christine Dunlap Farnham Archive.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown introduced graduate courses in the 1870s and granted its first advanced degrees in 1888.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The university established a Graduate Department in 1903 and a full Graduate School in 1927.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] With an enrollment of approximately 2,600 students, the school currently offers 33 and 51 master's and doctoral programs, respectively.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The school additionally offers a number of fifth-year master's programs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Overall, admission to the Graduate School is most competitive, with an acceptance rate averaging at approximately 9 percent in recent years.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Carney Institute for Brain Science is Brown's cross-departmental neuroscience research institute.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The institute's core focus areas include brain-computer interfaces and computational neuroscience; additional areas of focus include research into mechanisms of cell death with the interest of developing therapies for neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Carney Institute was founded by John Donoghue in 2009 as the Brown Institute for Brain Science and renamed in 2018 in recognition of a $100 million gift.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The donation, one of the largest in the university's history, established the institute as one of the best-endowed university neuroscience programs in the country.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Established in 1811, Brown's Alpert Medical School is the fourth oldest medical school in the Ivy League.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 1827, medical instruction was suspended by President Francis Wayland after the program's faculty declined to follow a new policy requiring students to live on campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The program was reorganized in 1972; the first M.D. degrees from the new Program in Medicine were awarded to a graduating class of 58 students in 1975.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 1991, the school was officially renamed the Brown University School of Medicine, then renamed once more to Brown Medical School in October 2000.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In January 2007, entrepreneur and philanthropist Warren Alpert donated $100 million to the school.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In recognition of the gift, the school's name was changed to the Warren Alpert Medical School of Brown University.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News & World Report* ranked Brown's medical school the 9th most selective in the country, with an acceptance rate of 2.8%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News* ranks the school 38th for research and 35th for primary care.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's medical school is known especially for its eight-year Program in Liberal Medical Education (PLME), an eight-year combined baccalaureate-M.D. medical program.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Inaugurated in 1984, the program is one of the most selective and renowned programs of its type in the country, offering admission to only 2% of applicants in 2021.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since 1976, the Early Identification Program (EIP) has encouraged Rhode Island residents to pursue careers in medicine by recruiting sophomores from Providence College, Rhode Island College, the University of Rhode Island, and Tougaloo College.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2004, the school once again began to accept applications from premedical students at other colleges and universities via AMCAS like most other medical schools.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The medical school also offers M.D./PhD, M.D./M.P.H. and M.D./M.P.P. dual degree programs.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's School of Public Health grew out of the Alpert Medical School's Department of Community Health and was officially founded in 2013 as an independent school.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Brown University School of Professional Studies currently offers blended learning Executive master's degrees in Healthcare Leadership, Cyber Security, and Science and Technology Leadership.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The master's degrees are designed to help students who have a job and life outside of academia to progress in their respective fields.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The students meet in Providence every 6–7 weeks for a weekly seminar each trimester.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The university has also invested in MOOC development starting in 2013, when two courses, *Archeology's Dirty Little Secrets* and *The Fiction of Relationship*, both of which received thousands of students.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] However, after a year of courses, the university broke its contract with Coursera and revamped its online persona and MOOC development department.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] By 2017, the university released new courses on edx, two of which were *The Ethics of Memory* and *Artful Medicine: Art's Power to Enrich Patient Care*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Undergraduate admission to Brown University is considered "most selective" by *U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News & World Report.* For the undergraduate class of 2026, Brown received 50,649 applications—the largest applicant pool in the university's history and a 9% increase from the prior year.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Of these applicants, 2,560 were admitted for an acceptance rate of 5.0%, the lowest in the university's history.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2021, the university reported a yield rate of 69%.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] For the academic year 2019–20 the university received 2,030 transfer applications, of which 5.8% were accepted.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's admissions policy is currently stipulated need-blind for all domestic first-year applicants, but will be extended to international first-year applicants starting with the Class of 2029.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2017, Brown announced that loans would be eliminated from all undergraduate financial aid awards starting in 2018–2019, as part of a new $30 million campaign called the *Brown Promise*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2016–17, the university awarded need-based scholarships worth $120.5 million.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The average need-based award for the class of 2020 was $47,940.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2017, the Graduate School accepted 11% of 9,215 applicants.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2021, Brown received a record 948 applications for roughly 90 spots in its Master of Public Health Degree.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News* ranked Brown's Warren Alpert Medical School the 9th most selective in the country, with an acceptance rate of 2.8 percent.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown University is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] For their 2021 rankings, *The Wall Street Journal*/*Times Higher Education* ranked Brown 5th in the "Best Colleges 2021" edition.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The *Forbes* magazine annual ranking of "America's Top Colleges 2022"—which ranked 600 research universities, liberal arts colleges and service academies—ranked Brown 19th overall and 18th among universities.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News & World Report* ranked Brown 129th globally.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2014, *Forbes* magazine ranked Brown 7th on its list of "America's Most Entrepreneurial Universities".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The *Forbes* analysis looked at the ratio of "alumni and students who have identified themselves as founders and business owners on LinkedIn" and the total number of alumni and students.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] LinkedIn particularized the *Forbes* rankings, placing Brown third (between MIT and Princeton) among "Best Undergraduate Universities for Software Developers at Startups".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] LinkedIn's methodology involved a career-path examination of "millions of alumni profiles" in its membership database.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2021, the university produced the most Fulbright recipients of any university in the nation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown has also produced the 7th most Rhodes Scholars of all colleges and universities in the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2025, the university ranked 229 of 257 top colleges in free speech rankings by the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression and "College Pulse", after ranking at 69 in 2024 and at 114 in 2022/2023.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown is a member of the Association of American Universities since 1933 and is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very High Research Activity".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In FY 2017, Brown spent $212.3 million on research and was ranked 103rd in the United States by total R&D expenditure by National Science Foundation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2021 Brown's School of Public Health received the 4th most funding in NIH awards among schools of public health in the U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Established in 1950, Spring Weekend is an annual spring music festival for students.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Historical performers at the festival have included Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, Ray Charles, Bob Dylan, Janis Joplin, Bruce Springsteen, and U2.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] More recent headliners include Kendrick Lamar, Young Thug, Daniel Caesar, Anderson .Paak, Mitski, Aminé, and Mac DeMarco.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since 1960, Spring Weekend has been organized by the student-run Brown Concert Agency.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Approximately 12 percent of Brown students participate in Greek life.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The university recognizes thirteen active Greek organizations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Since the early 1950s, all Greek organizations on campus have been located in Wriston Quadrangle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The earliest societies at Brown were devoted to oration and debate.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Pronouncing Society is mentioned in the diary of Solomon Drowne, class of 1773, who was voted its president in 1771.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The organization seems to have disappeared during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Subsequent societies include the Misokosmian Society (est.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] 1798 and renamed the Philermenian Society), the Philandrian Society (est.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] 1799), the United Brothers (1806), the Philophysian Society (1818), and the Franklin Society (1824).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Societies served social as well as academic purposes, with many supporting literary debate and amassing large libraries.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Older societies generally aligned with Federalists while younger societies generally leaned Republican.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Societies remained popular into the 1860s, after which they were largely replaced by fraternities.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Cammarian Club was at first a semi-secret society that "tapped" 15 seniors each year.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 1915, self-perpetuating membership gave way to popular election by the student body, and thenceforward the club served as the *de facto* undergraduate student government.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The organization was dissolved in 1971 and ultimately succeeded by a formal student government.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Societas Domi Pacificae, known colloquially as "Pacifica House", is a present-day, self-described secret society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] It purports a continuous line of descent from the Franklin Society of 1824, citing a supposed intermediary "Franklin Society" traceable in the nineteenth century.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] There are over 300 registered student organizations on campus with diverse interests.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Student Activities Fair, during the orientation program, provides first-year students the opportunity to become acquainted with a wide range of organizations.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2023, 38% of Brown's students identified as being LGBTQ+, in a poll by *The Brown Daily Herald*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] This was an increase of 14% over the LGBT self-identification in 2010.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] "Bisexual" was the most common answer among LGBTQ+ respondents to the poll.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown has several resource centers on campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The centers often act as sources of support as well as safe spaces for students to explore certain aspects of their identity.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Additionally, the centers often provide physical spaces for students to study and have meetings.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Although most centers are identity-focused, some provide academic support as well.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Brown Center for Students of Color (BCSC) is a space that provides support for students of color.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Established in 1972 at the demand of student protests, the BCSC encourages students to engage in critical dialogue, develop leadership skills, and promote social justice.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The center houses various programs for students to share their knowledge and engage in discussion.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Programs include the Third World Transition Program, the Minority Peer Counselor Program, the Heritage Series, and other student-led initiatives.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Additionally, the BCSC hopes to foster community among the students it serves by providing spaces for students to meet and study.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Sarah Doyle Women's Center aims to provide a space for members of the Brown community to examine and explore issues surrounding gender.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The center was named after one of the first women to attend Brown, Sarah Doyle.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The center emphasizes intersectionality in its conversations on gender, encouraging people to see gender as present and relevant in various aspects of life.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The center hosts programs and workshops in order to facilitate dialogue and provide resources for students, faculty, and staff.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Other centers include the LGBTQ Center, the Undocumented, First-Generation College and Low-Income Student (U-FLi) Center, and the Curricular Resource Center.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] On December 5, 1968, several Black women from Pembroke College initiated a walkout in protest of an atmosphere at the colleges described by Black students as a "stifling, frustrating, [and] degrading place for Black students" after feeling the colleges were non-responsive to their concerns.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In total, 65 Black students participated in the walkout.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Their principal demand was to increase Black student enrollment to 11% of the student populace, in an attempt to match that of the proportion in the US.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] This ultimately resulted in a 300% increase in Black enrollment the following year, but some demands have yet to be met.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In the 1990s, walls in women's bathrooms in the John D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Library were used to graffiti names of alleged male rapists.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The practice caused the school to re-evaluate how it handles sexual misbehaviour on campus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In the mid-1980s, under student pressure, the university divested from certain companies involved in South Africa.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Some students were still unsatisfied with partial divestment and began a fast in Manning Chapel and the university disenrolled them.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In April 1987, "dozens" of students interrupted a university corporation meeting, leading to 20 being put on probation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In 2013, students and Providence community members protested and disrupted a speech by then-NYPD Commissioner Raymond Kelly.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The incident was cited by Greg Lukianoff, president of the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression, as a high-profile example of a form of student protest questioning conceptions of free speech.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The incident was also the subject of a short critical documentary in 2016 by Brown alumnus Rob Montz.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In early November 2023, twenty students of Jewish background affiliated with the campus group "Jews for Ceasefire Now" (later renamed "Jews for Palestinian Liberation") staged a sit in at University Hall, resulting in their arrests by order of the University administration.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In the wake of the shooting, in early December 2023, forty-one more students held a sit-in with similar demands which resulted in additional arrests by the University.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The following semester, as the administration continued to press charges on the forty-one sit-in participants, nineteen students participated in an eight-day hunger strike preceding a corporation meeting with the demand to present their case to corporation members.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] In October 2024, the corporation held an early vote on the issue of divestment, rejecting the proposal in an 8-2 vote.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Following a University investigation into student protests resulting from this decision, the University suspended the Students for Justice in Palestine chapter at Brown.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown is a member of the Ivy League athletic conference, which is categorized as a Division I (top-level) conference of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Brown Bears has one of the largest university sports programs in the United States, sponsoring 32 varsity intercollegiate teams.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's athletic program is one of the *U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] News & World Report* top 20—the "College Sports Honor Roll"—based on breadth of the program and athletes' graduation rates.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's newest varsity team is women's rugby, promoted from club-sport status in 2014.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown women's rowing has won seven national titles between 1999 and 2011.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown men's rowing perennially finishes in the top 5 in the nation, most recently winning silver, bronze, and silver in the national championship races of 2012, 2013, and 2014.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The men's and women's crews have also won championship trophies at the Henley Royal Regatta and the Henley Women's Regatta.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown's men's soccer is consistently ranked in the top 20 and has won 18 Ivy League titles overall; recent soccer graduates play professionally in Major League Soccer and overseas.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Heisman, and Pollard Award namesake Fritz Pollard.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown women's gymnastics won the Ivy League tournament in 2013 and 2014.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The Brown women's sailing team has won five national championships, most recently in 2019, while the coed sailing team won two national championships in 1942 and 1948.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Both teams are consistency ranked in the top 10 in the nation.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The first intercollegiate ice hockey game in America was played between Brown and Harvard on January 19, 1898.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The first university rowing regatta larger than a dual-meet was held between Brown, Harvard, and Yale at Lake Quinsigamond in Massachusetts on July 26, 1859.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Brown also supports competitive intercollegiate club sports, including ultimate frisbee.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] The men's ultimate team, Brownian Motion, has won four national championships, in 2000, 2005, 2019 and 2024.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Alumni in politics and government include U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Secretary of State John Hay (1852), U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Attorney General Richard Olney (1856), Chief Justice of the United States and U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Secretary of State Charles Evans Hughes (1881), Governor of Wyoming Territory and Nebraska Governor John Milton Thayer (1841), Rhode Island Governor Augustus Bourn (1855), Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal '92, U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Prominent alumni in business and finance include philanthropist John D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] (1897), managing director of McKinsey & Company and "father of modern management consulting" Marvin Bower '25, former Chair of the Federal Reserve and current U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Secretary of the Treasury Janet Yellen '67, World Bank President Jim Yong Kim '82, Bank of America CEO Brian Moynihan '81, CNN founder Ted Turner '60, IBM chairman and CEO Thomas Watson Jr.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] '37, co-founder of Starwood Capital Group Barry Sternlicht '82, Apple Inc.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Chen '78, Facebook CFO David Ebersman '91, and Uber CEO Dara Khosrowshahi '91.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Companies founded by Brown alumni include CNN,*The Wall Street Journal,* Searchlight Pictures, Netgear, W Hotels, Workday, Warby Parker, Casper, Figma, ZipRecruiter, and Cards Against Humanity.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Alumni in the arts and media include actors Emma Watson '14, John Krasinski '01, Daveed Diggs '04, Julie Bowen '91, Tracee Ellis Ross '94, and Jessica Capshaw '98; NPR program host Ira Glass '82; singer-composer Mary Chapin Carpenter '81; humorist and Marx Brothers screenwriter S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Sulzberger '03, and magazine editor John F.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Important figures in the history of education include the father of American public school education Horace Mann (1819), civil libertarian and Amherst College president Alexander Meiklejohn, first president of the University of South Carolina Jonathan Maxcy (1787), Bates College founder Oren B.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Cheney (1836), University of Michigan president (1871–1909) James Burrill Angell (1849), University of California president (1899–1919) Benjamin Ide Wheeler (1875), and Morehouse College's first African-American president John Hope (1894).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Alumni in the computer sciences and industry include architect of Intel 386, 486, and Pentium microprocessors John H.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Crawford '75, inventor of the first silicon transistor Gordon Kidd Teal '31, MongoDB founder Eliot Horowitz '03, Figma founder Dylan Field, and Macintosh developer Andy Hertzfeld '75.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Other notable alumni include "Lafayette of the Greek Revolution" and its historian Samuel Gridley Howe (1821), NASA head during first seven Apollo missions Thomas O.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Paine '42, sportscaster Chris Berman '77, Houston Texans head coach Bill O'Brien '92, 2018 Miss America Cara Mund '16, Penn State football coach Joe Paterno '50, Heisman Trophy namesake John W.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Nobel Laureate alumni include humanitarian Jerry White '87 (Peace, 1997), biologist Craig Mello '82 (Physiology or Medicine, 2006), economist Guido Imbens (AM '89, PhD '91; Economic Sciences, 2021), and economist Douglas Diamond '75 (Economic Sciences, 2022).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Among Brown's past and present faculty are eight Nobel Laureates: Lars Onsager (Chemistry, 1968), Leon Cooper (Physics, 1972), George Snell (Physiology or Medicine, 1980), George Stigler (Economic Sciences, 1982), Henry David Abraham (Peace, 1985), Vernon L.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Michael Kosterlitz (Physics, 2016), Peter Howitt (Economic Sciences, 2025).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Notable past and present faculty include biologists Anne Fausto-Sterling (Ph.D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] 1970); computer scientists Robert Sedgewick and Andries van Dam; economists Hyman Minsky, Glenn Loury, George Stigler, Mark Blyth, and Emily Oster; historians Gordon S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Wood and Joan Wallach Scott; mathematicians David Gale, David Mumford, Mary Cartwright, and Solomon Lefschetz; physicists Sylvester James Gates and Gerald Guralnik.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Faculty in literature include Chinua Achebe, Ama Ata Aidoo, and Carlos Fuentes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Among Brown's faculty and fellows in political science, and public affairs are the former prime minister of Italy and former EU chief, Romano Prodi; former president of Brazil, Fernando Cardoso; former president of Chile, Ricardo Lagos; and son of Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev, Sergei Khrushchev.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Other faculty include philosopher Martha Nussbaum, author Ibram X.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Kendi, and public health doctor Ashish Jha.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] Mentions of Brown in fiction and popular culture include the following.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] *Family Guy* character Brian Griffin is a Brown alumnus.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brown-university-p02] *The O.C.*'s main character Seth Cohen is denied acceptance to Brown while his girlfriend Summer Roberts is accepted.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Settled in 1628 by Thomas Purchase and other fishermen, the area was called by its Indigenous Peoples' name, Pejepscot, meaning "the long, rocky rapids part [of the river]".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] In 1639, Purchase placed his settlement under protection of the Massachusetts Bay Colony.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] During King Philip's War in 1676, Pejepscot was burned and abandoned, although a garrison called Fort Andros was built on the ruins during King William's War.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] During the war, in Major Benjamin Church's second expedition a year later, he arrived on September 11, 1690, with 300 men at Casco Bay.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] He went up the Androscoggin River to Fort Pejepscot (present day Brunswick, Maine).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] From there he went 40 miles (64 km) upriver and attacked a native village.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Three or four native men were shot in retreat.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] When Church discovered five captive settlers in the wigwams, six or seven prisoners were butchered as an example, and nine prisoners were taken.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] A few days later, in retaliation, the natives attacked Church at Cape Elizabeth on Purpooduc Point, killing seven of his men and wounding 24 others.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] On September 26, Church returned to Portsmouth, New Hampshire.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The 1713 Treaty of Portsmouth brought peace to the region between the Abenaki Indians and the English colonists.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] In 1714, a consortium from Boston and Portsmouth bought the land, thereafter called the *Pejepscot purchase*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The Massachusetts General Court constituted the township in 1717, naming it "Brunswick" in honor of the House of Brunswick and its scion, King George I.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] A stone fort called Fort George was built in 1715 near the falls.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] But during Dummer's War on July 13, 1722, Abenaki warriors from Norridgewock burned the village.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Consequently, Governor Samuel Shute declared war on the Abenakis.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] In 1724, 208 English colonial militia left Fort Richmond and sacked Norridgewock during Dummer's War.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Brunswick was rebuilt again in 1727, and in 1739 incorporated as a town.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] It became a prosperous seaport, where Bowdoin College was chartered in 1794.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The Androscoggin River falls in three successive stages for a total vertical drop of 41 feet (12 m), providing water power for industry.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Brunswick became a major producer of lumber, with as many as 25 sawmills.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Some of the lumber went into shipbuilding.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Other firms produced paper, soap, flour, marble and granite work, carriages and harness, plows, furniture, shoes and confections.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The town was site of the first cotton mill in Maine, the Brunswick Cotton Manufactory Company, built in 1809 to make yarn.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Purchased in 1812, the mill was enlarged by the Maine Cotton & Woolen Factory Company.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] In 1857, the Cabot Manufacturing Company was established to make cotton textiles.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] It bought the failed Worumbo Mill and expanded the brick factory along the falls.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Needing even more room, the company in 1890 persuaded the town to move Maine Street.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Principal employers for Brunswick include L.L.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Bean, Bath Iron Works, as well as companies that produce fiberglass construction material and electrical switches.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] A number of health services providers serving Maine's mid-coast area are located in Brunswick.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The former Naval Air Station Brunswick was a major employer in Brunswick prior to its closure.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has an area of 54.34 square miles (140.74 km2), of which 46.73 square miles (121.03 km2) is land and 7.61 square miles (19.71 km2) is water.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Brunswick is at the north end of Casco Bay, as well as the head of tide and head of navigation on the Androscoggin River.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] It is the easternmost town in Cumberland County.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] As of 2000, the median income for a household in the town was $40,402; and the median income for a family was $49,088.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Males had a median income of $32,141 versus $24,927 for females.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The per capita income for the town was $20,322.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] About 5.0% of families and 8.0% of the population were below the poverty line, including 8.6% of those under age 18 and 8.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] As of the census of 2010, there were 15,175 people, 7,183 households, and 6,498 families residing in the census-designated place of Brunswick.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The population density was 433.9 inhabitants per square mile (167.5/km2).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] There were 9,599 housing units at an average density of 205.4 per square mile (79.3/km2).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The racial makeup of the town was 93.0% White, 1.7% African American, 0.3% Native American, 2.1% Asian, 0.5% from other races, and 2.4% from two or more races.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.9% of the population.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] There were 8,469 households, of which 25.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them; 44.7% were married couples living together; 9.7% had a female householder with no husband present; 3.3% had a male householder with no wife present; and 42.3% were non-families.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] 35.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 16.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The average household size was 2.19 and the average family size was 2.83.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The median age in the town was 41.4 years.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] 19.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 14.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 20.8% were from 25 to 44; 27.6% were from 45 to 64; and 18.2% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The gender makeup of the town was 47.1% male and 52.9% female.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The Growstown School, on Woodside Road, is the last remaining of the town's formerly twenty-six one-room schoolhouses.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Brunswick's sister city is Trinidad, Cuba.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The town is served by Interstate 295, U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Routes 1 and 201, and Maine State Route 24, Maine State Route 24 Business, Maine State Route 123 and Maine State Route 196.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Amtrak's *Downeaster* train service terminates at Brunswick station and connects the town to the Portland Transportation Center and Boston's North Station.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] Greater Portland Metro provides several trips a day between the Portland Transportation Center and Brunswick Maine Street Station with its Metro Breez bus service.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] A local bus service is provided by Brunswick Link.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] The book *Uncle Tom's Cabin* was written by Harriet Beecher Stowe while she was living in Brunswick, during the time that her husband was a professor at Bowdoin.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] She got a key vision for the book in the First Parish Church.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/brunswick-maine] A scene in the 1993 movie *The Man Without a Face* was filmed in the town.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] The son of a Church of England minister, Charles Valentine Riley was born on 19 September 1843 in London's Chelsea district.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] When he was around eleven his parents, the Rev.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Charles and Mary (née Valentine) Riley, chose to further his education in Europe.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] There he excelled at art and natural history attending private schools in Dieppe, France and later Bonn, Germany.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] After the death of his father he was brought home to Britain to enroll in a public school there.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Sometime later his mother remarried which may have played a part in his decision, taken at the age of seventeen, to cross the Atlantic Ocean to America with scant resources.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Riley's journey west ended in the U.S. state of Illinois where he was employed as a laborer on a farm in Aroma, a small community in Kankakee County some fifty miles south of Chicago.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Riley had become acquainted with the farm's owner, a British expatriate named George Edwards, sometime earlier when the latter was visiting London.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Around 1864 he left the Edwards’ farm to work for the Chicago-based *Prairie Farmer*, a leading agricultural journal as reporter, artist, and editor of the entomological department.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] A few months later he joined the 134th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment, mustering out before the end of 1864 after fulfilling his one-hundred day enlistment commitment.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] In 1868, he was appointed as the first State Entomologist for the State of Missouri.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He collaborated on the annual reports from Missouri, work which established him as one of the leading entomologists in the United States.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Riley studied the plague of grasshoppers that invaded many Western States between 1873 and 1877.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He convinced the United States Congress to establish the United States Entomological Commission, which included a Grasshopper Commission, to which Riley was appointed chairman.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] In 1876, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] In 1878, he was appointed to the post of entomologist to the U.S.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Department of Agriculture, but he resigned after only a year because of a disagreement with the Commissioner.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was reappointed in 1881 and remained in the top post until 1894.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was also appointed the first curator of insects for the Smithsonian Institution in 1885.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Riley would later go on to donate his 100,000 piece insect specimen collection to them.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was one of the first to practice biological pest control, introducing a beetle that was the natural enemy to a scale that was damaging the California citrus industry.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Because this method successfully reduced the scale, Riley is sometimes known as the "Father of Biological Control".
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He invented the “cyclone” or eddy chamber in nozzles for spraying purposes.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was among the first to notice that the American grapes, *Vitis labrusca* were resistant to grape *Phylloxera*.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Planchon led to the use of grafting French grape on *V. labrusca* root stock.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] This effort helped save the French wine industry and for his efforts, Riley received the French Grand Gold Medal and was named a Chevalier of the Legion of Honor in 1884.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] A prolific writer, artist, and visionary, Riley authored over 2,400 publications.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He published two journals, *The American Entomologist* (1868–80) and *Insect Life* (1889–94) and Riley was the first to recommend for the establishment of the Office of Experiment Stations, in 1878 before the National Agricultural Congress.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He received honorary degrees from Kansas State University and the University of Missouri.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was an honorary member of the Entomological Society of London and founder and first president of the Entomological Society of Washington.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Howard, Riley's assistant in the Federal Entomological Service, were among the founders of the American Association of Economic Entomologists, which became part of Entomological Society of America in 1953.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Riley was succeeded as State Entomologist of Missouri by Otto Lugger who served as an assistant in Riley's early years.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Louis, Missouri, Emilie Conzelman, who was born and raised in that city.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Her father, Gottlieb Conzelman, came from Germany and supported his family employed as a wallpaper hanger.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Emilie's mother, Jorgine Augusta (née Grønbech), was Danish; she died 21 February 1861 in St.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Charles and Emilie went on to have five girls and two boys.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Their first, Alice was born in 1879 and Cathryn, their youngest, came in 1891.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] William, Mary, Harold (who died at four months), Helen and Thora were all born in the 1880s.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] Emilie Conzelman Riley died at Washington D.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] C. on 10 December 1947, nearly a month shy of her 98th birthday (29 January 1948).
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] On 14 September 1895 Riley died as the result of a bicycle accident that occurred not far from his Washington, D.C., residence.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] As he was riding rapidly down a hill, the bicycle wheel struck a granite paving block dropped by a wagon.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He catapulted to the pavement and fractured his skull.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He was carried home on a wagon and never regained consciousness.
[src:alpheus-spring-packard/charles-valentine-riley] He died at his home the same day just short of the age of 52, leaving his widow with six children.
